\par Spencer shows that the early Liberal was consistently
\par for cutting down the State's coercive power over the citizen,
\par wherever this was possible. He was for reducing to a
\par minimum the number of points at which the State might
\par make coercive interventions upon the individual. He was
\par for steadily enlarging the margin of existence within which
\par the citizen might pursue and regulate his own activities as
\par he saw fit, free of, State control or State supervision. Liberal
\par policies and measures, as originally conceived, were such as
\par reflected these aims. The Tory, on the other hand, was
