\par opposed to these aims, and his policies reflected this opposition.
\par In general terms, the Liberal was consistently inclined
\par towards the individualist philosophy of society, while the
\par Tory was consistently inclined towards the Statist philosophy.
\par Spencer shows moreover that as a matter\'b7 of practical
\par policy, the early Liberal proceeded towards the realization
\par of his aims by the method of repeal. He was not for making
\par new laws, but for repealing old ones. It is most important
\par to remember this. Wherever the Liberal saw a law which
\par enhanced the State's coercive power over the citizen, he was
\par for repealing it and leaving its place blank. There were
\par many such laws on the British statute-books, and when Liberalism
\par came .into power it repealed an immense grist of
\par them.
